<subSubSection id="C5EA29EC7618FFDBFF47FF7A98A2FE9C" pageId="7" pageNumber="437" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8D4F7A677618FFDBFF47FF7A98A2FE9C" blockId="7.[151,1437,151,755]" pageId="7" pageNumber="437">
<emphasis id="BF84A6757618FFDBFF47FF7A9B84FF6F" bold="true" box="[199,742,151,176]" pageId="7" pageNumber="437">Variations on the specimens examined (n = 2).</emphasis>
The other female showed no variations on mesostigmal plates morphology; wing venation showed no variation in postquadrangular cells, RP2 branching or postnodal; size varied as follows: abdomen 31.8‒32.4 (32.1±0.4), total length 41.1‒42 (41.5±0.6), Fw 27.3–28 (27.6±0.4), Hw 26.6–27.3 (26.9±0.4). Body coloration variation for both females is shown in 
<figureCitation id="15CB66E27618FFDBFC11FEEB9D78FEC0" box="[913,1050,262,287]" captionStart="FIGURES 17‒24" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1877,1900]" captionTargetBox="[179,1302,1218,1783]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[149,1382,1189,1828]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 17‒24. Argia tupi (Calvert) BRAZIL: Chapada dos Guimarães; 17. S1‒10, ♀ (ACR 8184); 18. S1‒10, ♀ (ACR 8197); 19. head, ♀ (ACR 8184); 20. head, ♀ (ACR 8197); 21. S8‒10, ♀ (ACR 8184); 22. S8‒10, ♀ (ACR 8197); 23. thorax, ♀ (ACR 8197); 24. thorax, ♀ (ACR 8184)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1250857/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="437">Figs. 17‒24</figureCitation>
. The tan and blue coloration were darker in the other female.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C5EA29EC7618FFDBFF47FEA39B16FDBC" pageId="7" pageNumber="437" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8D4F7A677618FFDBFF47FEA39B16FDBC" blockId="7.[151,1437,151,755]" pageId="7" pageNumber="437">
<emphasis id="BF84A6757618FFDBFF47FEA398B2FEB8" bold="true" box="[199,464,334,359]" pageId="7" pageNumber="437">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
In contrast to 
<taxonomicName id="4AF001E47618FFDBFDFDFEA29A75FEB8" baseAuthorityName="Calvert" baseAuthorityYear="1909" box="[637,791,334,359]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Argia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="7" pageNumber="437" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicellulata">
<emphasis id="BF84A6757618FFDBFDFDFEA29A75FEB8" box="[637,791,334,359]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="437">A. bicellulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4AF001E47618FFDBFCA7FEA29A16FEB8" box="[807,884,335,359]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Argia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="7" pageNumber="437" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tupi">
<emphasis id="BF84A6757618FFDBFCA7FEA29A16FEB8" box="[807,884,335,359]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="437">A. tupi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is one of the largest Brazilian species occuring within Chapada. Apart from the large body size, 
<taxonomicName id="4AF001E47618FFDBFD50FE9E9A7CFE54" box="[720,798,371,395]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Argia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="7" pageNumber="437" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tupi">
<emphasis id="BF84A6757618FFDBFD50FE9E9A7CFE54" box="[720,798,371,395]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="437">A. tupi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
females can be separated from other Brazilian species, including 
<taxonomicName id="4AF001E47618FFDBFE8EFE7A98FEFE70" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1865" box="[270,412,406,431]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Argia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="7" pageNumber="437" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="clausseni">
<emphasis id="BF84A6757618FFDBFE8EFE7A98FEFE70" box="[270,412,406,431]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="437">A. clausseni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4AF001E47618FFDBFE5FFE7A9B1FFE70" box="[479,637,406,431]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Argia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="7" pageNumber="437" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cyathigera">
<emphasis id="BF84A6757618FFDBFE5FFE7A9B1FFE70" box="[479,637,406,431]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="437">A. cyathigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(females yet to be described by Rosser Garrison and Natalia von Ellenrieder) by the morphology of its mesostigmal lobes. In 
<taxonomicName id="4AF001E47618FFDBFCC3FE569AECFE0C" box="[835,910,443,467]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Argia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="7" pageNumber="437" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tupi">
<emphasis id="BF84A6757618FFDBFCC3FE569AECFE0C" box="[835,910,443,467]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="437">A. tupi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the short narrow mesostigmal lobe is strongly erect (
<figureCitation id="15CB66E27618FFDBFF5EFE339851FE28" box="[222,307,478,503]" captionStart="FIGURES 15‒16" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1135,1158]" captionTargetBox="[163,1407,505,1031]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[157,1429,483,1080]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 15‒16. Argia tupi (Calvert) BRAZIL: Serra do Cipó mesostigmal lobes; 15. ♀ dorsal view; 16. ♀ anterior view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1250855/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="437">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
), with a less rounded shape when compared to 
<taxonomicName id="4AF001E47618FFDBFCD7FE329A8AFE28" box="[855,1000,478,503]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Argia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="7" pageNumber="437" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="claussenii">
<emphasis id="BF84A6757618FFDBFCD7FE329A8AFE28" box="[855,1000,478,503]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="437">A. claussenii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="15CB66E27618FFDBFC79FE339DE0FE28" box="[1017,1154,478,503]" captionStart="FIGURES 25‒26" captionStartId="6.[151,264,699,722]" captionTargetBox="[180,1411,205,669]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[164,1424,193,678]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 25‒26. Argia claussenii (Selys) BRAZIL: Serra do Cipó mesostigmal lobes; 25. ♀ dorsal view; 26. ♀ anterior view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1250859/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="437">Figs. 25‒26</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="4AF001E47618FFDBFB44FE329C3FFE28" box="[1220,1373,478,503]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Argia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="7" pageNumber="437" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cyathigera">
<emphasis id="BF84A6757618FFDBFB44FE329C3FFE28" box="[1220,1373,478,503]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="437">A. cyathigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="15CB66E27618FFDBFAEEFE339983FDC4" captionStart="FIGURES 27‒28" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1319,1342]" captionTargetBox="[176,1407,807,1271]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,785,1298]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 27‒28. Argia cyathigera (Navás) BRAZIL: Nova Teutonia mesostigmal lobes; 27. ♀ dorsal view; 28. ♀ anterior view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1250861/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="437">Fig. 27‒28</figureCitation>
). The medio-apical portion of the lobe of 
<taxonomicName id="4AF001E47618FFDBFD39FDEE9A67FDC4" box="[697,773,515,539]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Argia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="7" pageNumber="437" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tupi">
<emphasis id="BF84A6757618FFDBFD39FDEE9A67FDC4" box="[697,773,515,539]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="437">A. tupi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lies somewhat diagonally in relation to the mesepisternum and is bent posteriorly, whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="4AF001E47618FFDBFDB1FDCA9BA6FDE0" box="[561,708,550,575]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Argia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="7" pageNumber="437" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="claussenii">
<emphasis id="BF84A6757618FFDBFDB1FDCA9BA6FDE0" box="[561,708,550,575]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="437">A. claussenii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="15CB66E27618FFDBFD57FDCB9A4EFDE0" box="[727,812,550,575]" captionStart="FIGURES 25‒26" captionStartId="6.[151,264,699,722]" captionTargetBox="[180,1411,205,669]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[164,1424,193,678]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 25‒26. Argia claussenii (Selys) BRAZIL: Serra do Cipó mesostigmal lobes; 25. ♀ dorsal view; 26. ♀ anterior view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1250859/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="437">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="4AF001E47618FFDBFCF2FDCA9D6EFDE0" box="[882,1036,550,575]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Argia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="7" pageNumber="437" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ciathygera">
<emphasis id="BF84A6757618FFDBFCF2FDCA9D6EFDE0" box="[882,1036,550,575]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="437">A. ciathygera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="15CB66E27618FFDBFB9FFDCB9D16FDE0" box="[1055,1140,550,575]" captionStart="FIGURES 27‒28" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1319,1342]" captionTargetBox="[176,1407,807,1271]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,785,1298]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 27‒28. Argia cyathigera (Navás) BRAZIL: Nova Teutonia mesostigmal lobes; 27. ♀ dorsal view; 28. ♀ anterior view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1250861/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="437">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
) these lobes are not bent posteriorly and have a larger foliate shape.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<paragraph id="8D4F7A677618FFDBFF47FD839AFAFD2D" blockId="7.[151,1437,151,755]" pageId="7" pageNumber="437">
<subSubSection id="C5EA29EC7618FFDBFF47FD839AF6FD2D" pageId="7" pageNumber="437" type="biology_ecology">
<emphasis id="BF84A6757618FFDBFF47FD8398AFFD58" bold="true" box="[199,461,622,647]" pageId="7" pageNumber="437">Habitats and Ecology.</emphasis>
This species was collected at a waterfall area in Chapada dos Guimarães National Park (
<figureCitation id="15CB66E27618FFDBFF1FFD7F9863FD74" box="[159,257,658,683]" captionStart="FIGURE 29" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1880,1902]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1422,1858]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,1422,1858]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 29 a‒b. Habitats of Argia tupi. 29a. Cachoeira do Marimbondo, natural habitat of Argia tupi; 29b. couple of Argia tupi at its natural habitat." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1250863/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="437">Fig. 29a</figureCitation>
). It inhabits the exposed streams above the waterfall and was found perched on the stones and vegetation around stream margin (
<figureCitation id="15CB66E27618FFDBFE1FFD5B9B61FD10" box="[415,515,694,719]" captionStart="FIGURE 29" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1880,1902]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1422,1858]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,1422,1858]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 29 a‒b. Habitats of Argia tupi. 29a. Cachoeira do Marimbondo, natural habitat of Argia tupi; 29b. couple of Argia tupi at its natural habitat." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1250863/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="437">Fig. 29b</figureCitation>
). Oviposition was observed in tandem, on the rocky walls of the waterfall, in the roots and other vegetal debris found on the rapid areas of the stream
</subSubSection>
.
</paragraph>
</treatment>
